        <label for="endHour">Hour</label>
        <select id="endHour">
          <option value="1">1</option>
          <option value="2">2</option>
          <option value="3">3</option>
          <option value="4">4</option>
          <option value="5" selected>5</option>
          <option value="6">6</option>
          <option value="7">7</option>
          <option value="8">8</option>
          <option value="9">9</option>
          <option value="10">10</option>
          <option value="11">11</option>
          <option value="12">12</option>
        </select>
      </div>
      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="endMin">Minute</label>
        <select id="endMin">
          <option value="0" selected>00</option>
          <option value="5">05</option>
          <option value="10">10</option>
          <option value="15">15</option>
          <option value="20">20</option>
          <option value="25">25</option>
          <option value="30">30</option>
          <option value="35">35</option>
          <option value="40">40</option>
          <option value="45">45</option>
          <option value="50">50</option>
          <option value="55">55</option>
        </select>
      </div>
      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="endAmpm">AM/PM</label>
        <select id="endAmpm">
          <option value="AM">AM</option>
          <option value="PM" selected>PM</option>
        </select>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="checkbox-row">
      <label class="checkbox-label">
        <input type="checkbox" id="nextDay" />
        End time is next day (crosses midnight)
      </label>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-bottom:24px;">
      <button class="calc-btn" id="calculateBtn">Calculate Hours</button>
    </div>

    <div class="calc-results" id="results" style="display:none;">
      <div class="result-cards">
        <div class="result-card primary">
          <span class="result-label">Formatted Duration</span>
          <span class="result-value" id="formattedResult">--</span>
        </div>
        <div class="result-card">
          <span class="result-label">Decimal Hours</span>
          <span class="result-value" id="decimalHours">--</span>
        </div>
        <div class="result-card">
          <span class="result-label">Total Minutes</span>
          <span class="result-value" id="totalMinutes">--</span>
        </div>
        <div class="result-card">
          <span class="result-label">Total Hours</span>
          <span class="result-value" id="totalHours">--</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div id="breakdown" class="breakdown-box"></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <AdUnit slot="calc-mid" format="rectangle" />

  <article class="content-section">
    <h2>How to Calculate Hours Between Two Times</h2>
    <p>Calculating the number of hours between two times is a common task for tracking work hours, planning schedules, managing projects, and filling out timesheets. While the math is straightforward in concept, it can become confusing when dealing with AM and PM transitions, midnight crossings, and the need to convert between different time formats. This calculator handles all of those complexities for you.</p>
    <p>The fundamental approach is simple: convert both times to a common format (typically 24-hour or total minutes from midnight), then subtract the start from the end. If the result is negative (meaning the end time is on the following day), add 24 hours to get the correct duration. The result can then be expressed in hours and minutes, total minutes, or decimal hours depending on what your application requires.</p>

    <h2>Step-by-Step Manual Calculation</h2>
    <p>To calculate the hours between two times manually, follow these steps:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Convert both times to 24-hour format:</strong> For AM times, keep the hour as-is (12 AM = 0). For PM times, add 12 (except 12 PM stays as 12). For example, 9:00 AM = 9:00, 5:30 PM = 17:30, 12:00 AM = 0:00, 12:00 PM = 12:00.</li>
      <li><strong>Convert to total minutes:</strong> Multiply hours by 60 and add minutes. 9:00 AM = 540 minutes. 5:30 PM = 1,050 minutes.</li>
      <li><strong>Subtract start from end:</strong> 1,050 - 540 = 510 minutes.</li>
      <li><strong>Convert back:</strong> 510 minutes = 8 hours and 30 minutes (510 / 60 = 8.5 decimal hours).</li>
    </ol>
    <p><strong>Midnight crossing example:</strong> From 10:00 PM to 6:00 AM the next day. 10:00 PM = 1,320 minutes. 6:00 AM = 360 minutes. Since 360 &lt; 1,320, add 1,440 (24 hours in minutes): 360 + 1,440 = 1,800. Then: 1,800 - 1,320 = 480 minutes = 8 hours.</p>

    <h2>Decimal Hours Explained</h2>
    <p>Decimal hours express time as a single number with a decimal fraction, which is essential for payroll calculations, project billing, and time tracking software. Instead of saying "2 hours and 45 minutes," the decimal equivalent is 2.75 hours. This format makes mathematical operations straightforward—you can simply add, subtract, multiply, and divide without worrying about base-60 conversions.</p>
    <p>Here are the most common minute-to-decimal conversions:</p>
    <table class="info-table" style="max-width:100%;">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Minutes</th><th>Decimal</th><th>Minutes</th><th>Decimal</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>5 min</td><td>0.08</td><td>35 min</td><td>0.58</td></tr>
        <tr><td>10 min</td><td>0.17</td><td>40 min</td><td>0.67</td></tr>
        <tr><td>15 min</td><td>0.25</td><td>45 min</td><td>0.75</td></tr>
        <tr><td>20 min</td><td>0.33</td><td>50 min</td><td>0.83</td></tr>
        <tr><td>25 min</td><td>0.42</td><td>55 min</td><td>0.92</td></tr>
        <tr><td>30 min</td><td>0.50</td><td>60 min</td><td>1.00</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>To convert any number of minutes to decimal, simply divide by 60. To convert decimal back to minutes, multiply the decimal part by 60. For example, 3.83 hours = 3 hours + (0.83 &times; 60) = 3 hours and 50 minutes.</p>

    <h2>Work Hours and Timesheet Calculations</h2>
    <p>The most common application of hours calculation is tracking work hours for payroll. Most employers require employees to record their start and end times, then calculate the total hours worked. Here is a typical workflow:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Record clock-in and clock-out times:</strong> For example, 8:30 AM to 5:15 PM.</li>
      <li><strong>Calculate gross hours:</strong> 5:15 PM minus 8:30 AM = 8 hours 45 minutes = 8.75 hours.</li>
      <li><strong>Subtract unpaid breaks:</strong> If you took a 30-minute lunch, subtract 0.5 hours: 8.75 - 0.50 = 8.25 hours worked.</li>
      <li><strong>Calculate weekly totals:</strong> Add each day's decimal hours. Five days at 8.25 hours = 41.25 hours per week.</li>
      <li><strong>Determine overtime:</strong> In the US, hours over 40 per week are typically paid at 1.5x the regular rate. In this example, 1.25 hours would be overtime.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Many payroll systems round time to the nearest quarter hour (15-minute increments). Under this system, 8:07 AM rounds to 8:00 AM, and 8:08 AM rounds to 8:15 AM. The exact rounding rules vary by employer and are governed by the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA) in the United States.</p>

    <h2>Overtime Rules in the United States</h2>
    <p>Under the Fair Labor Standards Act, non-exempt employees must be paid at least 1.5 times their regular rate for all hours worked over 40 in a workweek. Some states have additional rules:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>California:</strong> Daily overtime after 8 hours, double time after 12 hours, and weekly overtime after 40 hours.</li>
      <li><strong>Colorado:</strong> Daily overtime after 12 hours and weekly overtime after 40 hours.</li>
      <li><strong>Alaska:</strong> Daily overtime after 8 hours and weekly overtime after 40 hours.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>For salaried exempt employees, overtime rules typically do not apply. However, the salary threshold for exemption has been updated multiple times. Always check current federal and state guidelines for the most up-to-date thresholds.</p>

    <h2>Night Shifts and Crossing Midnight</h2>
    <p>Calculating hours for night shifts that cross midnight requires special attention. If a nurse works from 7:00 PM to 7:00 AM, the calculation must account for the day change. The simplest method is to check the "End time is next day" option in the calculator, which automatically adds 24 hours before computing the difference.</p>
    <p>For manual calculation, if the end time is earlier than the start time on the clock, add 24 hours (1,440 minutes) to the end time before subtracting. A shift from 11:00 PM (23:00) to 7:30 AM (7:30) becomes: (7:30 + 24:00) &minus; 23:00 = 31:30 &minus; 23:00 = 8 hours 30 minutes.</p>
    <p>Some employers split overnight shifts into two calendar days for payroll purposes. For example, a 10 PM to 6 AM shift might be recorded as 2 hours on Day 1 (10 PM to midnight) and 6 hours on Day 2 (midnight to 6 AM). This matters when calculating daily overtime in states like California.</p>

    <h2>Time Formats Around the World</h2>
    <p>Different countries and industries use different time formats, which affects how hours are recorded and calculated:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>12-hour format (AM/PM):</strong> Standard in the United States, Canada, Australia, and the Philippines. Ranges from 12:00 AM (midnight) to 12:59 AM, then 1:00 AM to 11:59 AM, then 12:00 PM (noon) to 11:59 PM.</li>
      <li><strong>24-hour format (military time):</strong> Standard in most of Europe, Latin America, Asia, and Africa, as well as military, aviation, healthcare, and emergency services worldwide. Ranges from 00:00 to 23:59.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The 24-hour format eliminates ambiguity (there is no confusion between 9 AM and 9 PM) and simplifies calculations since there is no need to convert between AM and PM. This is why it is preferred in technical and safety-critical fields.</p>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How do I calculate hours between two times?</summary>
        <p>Convert both times to 24-hour format, then subtract the start from the end. For AM times, keep the hour as-is (12 AM becomes 0). For PM times, add 12 to the hour (except 12 PM stays as 12). If the end time is smaller than the start time, the period crosses midnight, so add 24 hours to the end before subtracting. Example: 9:00 AM to 5:30 PM = 17:30 &minus; 9:00 = 8 hours 30 minutes.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How do I convert decimal hours to hours and minutes?</summary>
        <p>The whole number is the hours. Multiply the decimal fraction by 60 to get minutes. For example, 6.75 hours: the whole number is 6 hours, and 0.75 &times; 60 = 45 minutes, giving 6 hours and 45 minutes. To go the other direction, divide minutes by 60 and add to hours: 6 hours 45 minutes = 6 + (45/60) = 6.75 hours.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How do I calculate work hours for a timesheet?</summary>
        <p>Enter your clock-in time as the start and clock-out time as the end. The calculator gives you the gross hours. Then subtract any unpaid break time (typically 30 or 60 minutes for lunch). For weekly totals, add each day's decimal hours together. Hours over 40 per week are usually overtime in the US. If you work overnight, check the "End time is next day" box.</p>
      </details>
    </div>

    <h2>Related Calculators</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/date-time-calculators/time-duration-calculator/">Time Duration Calculator</a> - Add or subtract hours and minutes.</li>
      <li><a href="/date-time-calculators/date-difference-calculator/">Date Difference Calculator</a> - Find the days between two dates.</li>
      <li><a href="/date-time-calculators/business-days-calculator/">Business Days Calculator</a> - Count working days between dates.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>

  <AdUnit slot="calc-bottom" format="horizontal" />
  <RelatedArticles calculatorSlug="hours-calculator" />
  <RelatedCalculators currentSlug="hours-calculator" />
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .section-label {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin: 0 0 8px;
    color: var(--color-text);
  }
  .time-row {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr) !important;
    margin-bottom: 16px !important;
  }
  .checkbox-row {
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }
  .checkbox-label {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 8px;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    cursor: pointer;
  }
  .checkbox-label input[type="checkbox"] {
    width: 18px;
    height: 18px;
    cursor: pointer;
  }
  .breakdown-box {
    margin-top: 16px;
    padding: 12px 16px;
    background: var(--color-bg);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }
  .last-updated { font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin: 4px 0 0; }
  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .time-row { grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr) !important; }
    .result-cards { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
  }
</style>

<script is:inline>
  function to24(hour, ampm) {
    var h = parseInt(hour);
    if (ampm === 'AM') {
      return h === 12 ? 0 : h;
    } else {
      return h === 12 ? 12 : h + 12;
    }
  }

  function calculateHours() {
    var startH = to24(document.getElementById('startHour').value, document.getElementById('startAmpm').value);
    var startM = parseInt(document.getElementById('startMin').value);
    var endH = to24(document.getElementById('endHour').value, document.getElementById('endAmpm').value);
    var endM = parseInt(document.getElementById('endMin').value);
    var nextDay = document.getElementById('nextDay').checked;

    var startTotal = startH * 60 + startM;
    var endTotal = endH * 60 + endM;

    if (nextDay) {
      endTotal += 1440;
    } else if (endTotal <= startTotal) {
      endTotal += 1440;
    }

    var diffMin = endTotal - startTotal;
    if (diffMin < 0) diffMin = 0;

    var hours = Math.floor(diffMin / 60);
    var mins = diffMin % 60;
    var decimal = (diffMin / 60).toFixed(2);

    // Formatted result
    var formatted = '';
    if (hours > 0 && mins > 0) {
      formatted = hours + (hours === 1 ? ' hour ' : ' hours ') + mins + (mins === 1 ? ' minute' : ' minutes');
    } else if (hours > 0) {
      formatted = hours + (hours === 1 ? ' hour' : ' hours');
    } else {
      formatted = mins + (mins === 1 ? ' minute' : ' minutes');
    }

    document.getElementById('formattedResult').textContent = formatted;
    document.getElementById('decimalHours').textContent = decimal + ' hrs';
    document.getElementById('totalMinutes').textContent = diffMin.toLocaleString() + ' min';
    document.getElementById('totalHours').textContent = hours + (hours === 1 ? ' hr' : ' hrs');

    // Build breakdown
    var startStr = document.getElementById('startHour').value + ':' + (startM < 10 ? '0' : '') + startM + ' ' + document.getElementById('startAmpm').value;
    var endStr = document.getElementById('endHour').value + ':' + (endM < 10 ? '0' : '') + endM + ' ' + document.getElementById('endAmpm').value;
    if (nextDay) endStr += ' (next day)';

    var breakdown = '<strong>From:</strong> ' + startStr + '<br>';
    breakdown += '<strong>To:</strong> ' + endStr + '<br>';
    breakdown += '<strong>Duration:</strong> ' + formatted + ' (' + decimal + ' decimal hours)<br>';
    breakdown += '<strong>Total minutes:</strong> ' + diffMin.toLocaleString();
    document.getElementById('breakdown').innerHTML = breakdown;

    document.getElementById('results').style.display = 'block';
  }

  document.getElementById('calculateBtn').addEventListener('click', calculateHours);
  calculateHours();
</script>
